<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-591-380  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 591 380.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 25 1990 v24 n26 p93(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>U.S. waning, Japan gaining: 'ad hoc' industrial policy is hobblinghardware industry, Commerce report says. (U.S. Dept of Commercereport, 'The Competitive Status of the U.S. Electronics Sector,'rips Bush administration policy)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Betts, Mitch.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A report on the international electronic industry released by theUS Commerce Department criticizes the policies of the Bushadministration.andP;  The report, entitled 'The Competitive Status ofthe US Electronics Sector,' notes that the US is on track to bereplaced as the world's largest producer and trader of electronicsgoods within the next few years.andP;  The US still leads in productionand consumption volume, employment and technology base, theCommerce Dept says, but trails Japan and South Korea in othercrucial categories.andP;  The report said that the mismanagement andshort-sightedness of current administration policies, which amountto an 'ad hoc' approach that refuses to engage in strategicplanning, opposes a unified industrial policy that would providegovernment support for critical US industries and amounts to alaissez-faire economic policy that is placing the US at risk.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Department of CommerceIndustry AnalysisForeign CompetitionStrategic PlanningGovernment FundingElectronic Industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Top three countries in electronics industry areas. (table)Person:    Bush, George (commercial policy).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>